NHL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CANADIENS HOLD OFF JETS, 4-3, ON ROOKIE'S THIRD-PERIOD GOAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN HAFNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Andrew Cassels scored in a wild scramble halfway through the third period at 
Montreal Sunday night and the Canadiens avoided consecutive defeats at home. 
</P>
<P>
Although outplaying the Winnipeg Jets most of the game, the Canadiens, losers 
Saturday night to the Kings, were tied. 
</P>
<P>
But Cassels, a rookie center, picked up a loose puck and shot through a maze of 
bodies past goaltender Bob Essena to give the Canadiens a 4-3 victory. 
</P>
<P>
The Canadiens outshot the Jets, 44-26. Stephen Lebeau had two goals and Guy 
Carbonneau had the other for the Canadiens, who had 14 shots in the first 
period and scored on Lebeau's power-play shot. 
</P>
