<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: VENTURA; 
</P>
<P>
SURFBOARDS SHAPE UP AS A SECOND JOB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOEL BRAND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When a real estate agent sells a house, it is common practice for the agent to 
give a small gift to the buyer. For Dave Wallace, an agent with Don L. Carlton 
Realtors in Ventura, the gift is often one of his hand-crafted surfboards. 
</P>
<P>
Each week Wallace shapes 15 surfboards that are sold in area surf shops. Under 
the brand name Vector Vehicles, the surfboards are popular locally, said Vince 
Felix, a salesman at Waveline Ventura, one of the shops that carries the line 
of boards. 
</P>
<P>
"I basically have two full-time jobs," Wallace said. "I can go in and shape 
surfboards in the morning, be done by 12 p.m. and be in the real estate office 
by 1 p.m. It works out well." 
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ventura resident has been shaping surfboards since 1967. "I 
think the first one I shaped was for my sister, then I shaped one for myself 
and pretty soon I just started shaping boards for all my friends," Wallace 
said. "It took off from there." 
</P>
<P>
In 1969, a Ventura surf shop hired Wallace, then a 16-year-old high school 
student, to make surfboards. He has been crafting boards ever since, about 
10,000 or so to date. His short boards, popular among younger surfers, sell for 
about $300. His long-board designs retail at about $400. 
</P>
<P>
For several years, Wallace sold his surfboards from a surf shop he owned in 
Oxnard, but he tired of running a retail store. Five years ago, he decided to 
take up real estate to supplement his income from Vector Vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
The combination of the two jobs has worked out well for Wallace. For instance, 
he recently received an increase in surfboard orders that partially offsets the 
slump in real-estate sales. More than just a moneymaker, board-making is 
Wallace's passion. 
</P>
<P>
"Real estate is going to be a lot more financially rewarding than shaping surf 
boards is ever going to be, but shaping is therapeutic," he said. JOEL BRAND 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Dave Wallace measures a surfboard's bottom curve with a custom rocker 
jig. GEORGE WOLF / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
